# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: asgard-archaea
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala were long thought to be a discrete phylum.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Recent genome analysis has shown that they are descended from, and should be considered as, highly modified rotifers.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] This unified taxon is sometimes known as Syndermata, or simply as Rotifera, with the acanthocephalans described as a subclass of a rotifer class Hemirotatoria.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The earliest recognisable description of Acanthocephala – a worm with a proboscis armed with hooks – was made by Italian author Francesco Redi (1684).
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] In 1771, Joseph Koelreuter proposed the name Acanthocephala.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Philipp Ludwig Statius Müller independently called them *Echinorhynchus* in 1776.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Karl Rudolphi in 1809 formally named them Acanthocephala.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The oldest known member of the group is the Middle Jurassic (living approximately 165 million years ago) taxon *Juracanthocephalus daohugouensis* known from the Jiulongshan Formation (China).
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The fossil record of the group also includes eggs found in a coprolite from the Late Cretaceous Bauru Group of Brazil, around 70–80 million years old, likely from a crocodyliform.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The group may have originated substantially earlier.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans are highly adapted to a parasitic mode of life, and have lost many organs and structures through evolutionary processes.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] This makes determining relationships with other higher taxa through morphological comparison problematic.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] A 2016 phylogenetic analysis of the gene order in the mitochondria suggests that Seisonidea and Acanthocephala are sister clades and that the Eurotatoria are the sister clade to this group, producing the cladogram below.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Several morphological characteristics distinguish acanthocephalans from other phyla of parasitic worms.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans lack a mouth or alimentary canal.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] This is a feature they share with the cestoda (tapeworms), although the two groups are not closely related.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Adult stages live in the intestines of their host and uptake nutrients which have been digested by the host, directly, through their body surface.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The acanthocephalans lack an excretory system, although some species have been shown to possess flame cells (protonephridia).
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The most notable feature of the acanthocephala is the presence of an anterior, protrudable proboscis that is usually covered with spiny hooks (hence the common name: thorny or spiny headed worm).
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The proboscis bears rings of recurved hooks arranged in horizontal rows, and it is by means of these hooks that the animal attaches itself to the tissues of its host.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The hooks may be of two or three shapes, usually: longer, more slender hooks are arranged along the length of the proboscis, with several rows of more sturdy, shorter nasal hooks around the base of the proboscis.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The proboscis is used to pierce the gut wall of the final host, and hold the parasite fast while it completes its life cycle.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Like the body, the proboscis is hollow, and its cavity is separated from the body cavity by a *septum* or *proboscis sheath*.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Traversing the cavity of the proboscis are muscle-strands inserted into the tip of the proboscis at one end and into the septum at the other.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Their contraction causes the proboscis to be invaginated into its cavity.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The whole proboscis apparatus can also be, at least partially, withdrawn into the body cavity, and this is effected by two retractor muscles which run from the posterior aspect of the septum to the body wall.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Some of the acanthocephalans (perforating acanthocephalans) can insert their proboscis in the intestine of the host and open the way to the abdominal cavity.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The size of these animals varies greatly, ranging from a few millimetres in length to *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus*, which measures from 10 to 65 centimetres (3.9 to 25.6 in).
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] A curious feature shared by both larva and adult is the large size of many of the cells, e.g. the nerve cells and cells forming the uterine bell.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Polyploidy is common, with up to 343n having been recorded in some species.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The body surface of the acanthocephala is peculiar.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Externally, the skin has a thin tegument that covers the epidermis and consists of a syncytium with no cell walls.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The syncytium is traversed by a series of branching tubules containing fluid and is controlled by a few wandering, amoeboid nuclei.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Inside the syncytium is an irregular layer of circular muscle fibres, and within this again some rather scattered longitudinal fibres; there is no endothelium.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] In their micro-structure the muscular fibres resemble those of nematodes.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Except for the absence of the longitudinal fibres the skin of the proboscis resembles that of the body, but the fluid-containing tubules of the proboscis are shut off from those of the body.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The canals of the proboscis open into a circular vessel which runs round its base.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] From the circular canal two sac-like projections called the *lemnisci* run into the cavity of the body, alongside the proboscis cavity.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Each consists of a prolongation of the syncytial material of the proboscis skin, penetrated by canals and sheathed with a muscular coat.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] They seem to act as reservoirs into which the fluid which is used to keep the proboscis "erect" can withdraw when it is retracted, and from which the fluid can be driven out when it is wished to expand the proboscis.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The central ganglion of the nervous system lies behind the proboscis sheath or septum.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] It innervates the proboscis and projects two stout trunks posteriorly which supply the body.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Each of these trunks is surrounded by muscles, and this nerve-muscle complex is called a *retinaculum*.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] In the male at least there is also a genital ganglion.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Some scattered papillae may possibly be sense-organs.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans have complex life cycles, involving a number of hosts, for both developmental and resting stages.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Complete life cycles have been worked out for only 25 species.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala are dioecious (an individual organism is either male or female).
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] There is a structure called the *genital ligament* which runs from the posterior end of the proboscis sheath to the posterior end of the body.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] In the male, two testes lie on either side of this.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Each opens in a vas deferens which bears three diverticula or *vesiculae seminales*.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The male also possesses three pairs of cement glands, found behind the testes, which pour their secretions through a duct into the vasa deferentia.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] These unite and end in a penis which opens posteriorly.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] In the female, the ovaries are found, like the testes, as rounded bodies along the ligament.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] From the ovaries, masses of ova dehisce into the body cavity, floating in its fluids for fertilization by male's sperm.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] After fertilization, each egg contains a developing embryo.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] (These embryos hatch into first stage larva.) The fertilized eggs are brought into the uterus by actions of the *uterine bell*, a funnel like opening continuous with the uterus.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] At the junction of the bell and the uterus there is a second, smaller opening situated dorsally.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The bell "swallows" the matured eggs and passes them on into the uterus.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] (Immature embryos are passed back into the body cavity through the dorsal opening.) From the uterus, mature eggs leave the female's body via her oviduct, pass into the host's alimentary canal and are expelled from the host's body within feces.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Having been expelled by the female, the acanthocephalan egg is released along with the feces of the host.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] For development to occur, the egg, containing the acanthor, needs to be ingested by an arthropod, usually a crustacean (there is one known life cycle which uses a mollusc as a first intermediate host).
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Inside the intermediate host, the acanthor is released from the egg and develops into an acanthella.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] It then penetrates the gut wall, moves into the body cavity, encysts, and begins transformation into the infective cystacanth stage.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] This form has all the organs of the adult save the reproductive ones.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The parasite is released when the first intermediate host is ingested.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] This can be by a suitable final host, in which case the cystacanth develops into a mature adult, or by a paratenic host, in which the parasite again forms a cyst.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] When consumed by a suitable final host, the cycstacant *excysts*, everts its proboscis and pierces the gut wall.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] It then feeds, grows and develops its sexual organs.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The male uses the excretions of its *cement glands* to plug the vagina of the female, preventing subsequent matings from occurring.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Embryos develop inside the female, and the life cycle repeats.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Thorny-headed worms begin their life cycle inside invertebrates that reside in marine or freshwater systems.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] One example is *Polymorphus paradoxus.* *Gammarus lacustris*, a small crustacean that inhabits ponds and rivers, is one invertebrate that *P. paradoxus* may occupy; ducks are one of the definitive hosts.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] This crustacean is preyed on by ducks and hides by avoiding light and staying away from the surface.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] However, infection by *P. paradoxus* changes its behavior and appearance in a number of ways that increase its chance of being eaten.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] First, infection significantly reduces *G. lacustris'*s photophobia; as a result, it becomes attracted toward light and swims to the surface.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Second, an infected organism will even go so far as to find a rock or a plant on the surface, clamp its mouth down, and latch on, making it easy prey for the duck.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Finally, infection reduces the pigment distribution and amount in *G. lacustris,* causing the host to turn blue; unlike their normal brown colour, this makes the crustacean stand out and increases the chance the duck will see it.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Experiments have shown that altered serotonin levels are likely responsible for at least some of these changes in behaviour.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] One experiment found that serotonin induces clinging behavior in *G. lacustris* similar to that seen in infected organisms.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Another showed that infected *G. lacustris* had approximately 3 times as many serotonin-producing sites in its ventral nerve cord.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalosis, a disease caused by *Acanthacephalus* infection, is prevalent in aquaculture, occurring in Atlantic salmon, rainbow and brown trout, tilapia, and tambaqui.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Increasing occurrence in Brazilian farming of tambaqui has been reported, and in 2003 *Acanthacephalus* was first reported in cultured red snapper in Taiwan.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The life cycle of *Polymorphus* spp. normally occurs between sea ducks (e.g. eiders and scoters) and small crabs.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Infections found in commercial-sized lobsters in Canada were probably acquired from crabs that form an important dietary item of lobsters.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Cystacanths occurring in lobsters can cause economic loss to fishermen.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] There are no known methods of prevention or control.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Although they rarely infect humans, worms in the phylum Acanthocephala cause the disease acanthocephaliasis in humans.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The earliest known infection was found in a prehistoric man in Utah.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] This infection was dated to 1869 ± 160 BC.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The species involved was thought to be *Moniliformis clarki* which is still common in the area.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The first report of an isolate in historic times was by Lambl in 1859 when he isolated *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus* from a child in Prague.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Lindemann in 1865 reported that this organism was commonly isolated in Russia.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The reason for this was discovered by Schneider in 1871 when he found that an intermediate host, the scarabaeid beetle grub, was commonly eaten raw.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] The first report of clinical symptoms was by Calandruccio who in 1888 while in Italy infected himself by ingesting larvae.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] He reported gastrointestinal disturbances and shed eggs in two weeks.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Subsequent natural infections have since been reported.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Eight species have been isolated from humans to date.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] *Moniliformis moniliformis* is the most common isolate.
[src:asgard-archaea/acanthocephala] Other isolates include *Acanthocephalus bufonis* and *Corynosoma strumosum*.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Members of this phylum are physiologically diverse, and can be found in a variety of environments including soil, decomposing wood, hot springs, oceans, caves, and metal-contaminated soils.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] The members of this phylum are particularly abundant in soil habitats representing up to 52% of the total bacterial community.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Environmental factors such as pH and nutrients have been seen to drive Acidobacteriota dynamics.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Many Acidobacteriota are acidophilic, including the first described member of the phylum, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] There is much that is unknown about Acidobacteria both in their form and function.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Thus, this is a growing field of microbiology.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Some of this uncertainty can be attributed to the difficulty with which these bacteria are grown in the laboratory.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] There has been recent success in propagation by using low concentrations of nutrients in combination with high amounts of CO2, yet, progress is still quite slow.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] These new methods have only allowed approximately 30% of subdivisions to have species documented.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Additionally, many of the samples sequenced do not have taxonomic names as they have not yet been fully characterized.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] This area of study is a very current topic, and scientific understanding is expected to grow and change as new information comes to light.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Other notable species are *Holophaga foetida*, *Geothrix fermentans*, *Acanthopleuribacter pedis* and *Bryobacter aggregatus*.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Since they have only recently been discovered and the large majority have not been cultured, the ecology and metabolism of these bacteria is not well understood.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] However, these bacteria may be an important contributor to ecosystems, since they are particularly abundant within soils.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivisions 1, 4, and 6 are found to be particularly abundant in soils.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] As well as their natural soil habitat, unclassified subdivision 2 Acidobacteriota have also been identified as a contaminant of DNA extraction kit reagents, which may lead to their erroneous appearance in microbiota or metagenomic datasets.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 have been found to dominate in low pH conditions.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Additionally, Acidobacteriota from acid mine drainage have been found to be more adapted to acidic pH conditions (pH 2–3) compared to Acidobacteriota from soils, potentially due to cell specialization and enzyme stability.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] The G+C content of Acidobacteria genomes are consistent within their subdivisions - above 60% for group V fragments and roughly 10% lower for group III fragments.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] The majority of Acidobacteriota are considered aerobes.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] There are some Acidobacteriota that are considered anaerobes within subdivision 8 and subdivision 23.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] It has been found that some strains of Acidobacteriota originating from soils have the genomic potential to respire oxygen at atmospheric and sub-atmospheric concentrations.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Members of the *Acidobacteriota* phylum have been considered oligotrophic bacteria due to high abundances in low organic carbon environments.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] However, the variation in this phylum may indicate that they may not have the same ecological strategy.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] The first species, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*, of this phylum was discovered in 1991.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] However, Acidobacteriota were not recognized as a distinct clade until 1997, and were not recognized as a phylum until 2012.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] In an effort to further classify Acidobacteria, 16S rRNA gene regions were sequenced from many different strains.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] These sequences lead to the formation of subdivisions within the phyla.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Today, there are 26 accepted subdivisions recognized in the Ribosomal Database Project.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Much of this variety comes from populations of acidobacteria found in soils contaminated with uranium.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Therefore, most of the known species in this phyla are concentrated in a few of the subdivisions, the largest being #1.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Most of these microbes are aerobes, and they are all heterotrophic.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Subdivision 1 contains 11 of the known genera in addition to the majority of the species that have been able to be cultivated thus far.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Within the 22 known genera, there are 40 conclusive species.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] The genera are divided amongst subdivisions 3, 4, 8, 10, 23, and 1.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] As the Acidobateria are a developing area of microbiology, it is hypothesized that these numbers will change drastically with further study.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Some members of subdivision 1 are able to use D-glucose, D-xylose, and lactose as carbon sources, but are unable to use fucose or sorbose.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 also contain enzymes such as galactosidases used in the breakdown of sugars.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 4 have been found to use chitin as a carbon source.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Despite the presence of genetic information generally known to encode for carbohydrate processing machinery in various genera of Acidobacteria, several experimental studies have demonstrated the inability to break down various polysaccharides.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Cellulose is the main component of plant cell walls and a seemingly opportune resource for carbon.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] However, only a single species across all subdivisions has been shown to process it, *Telmactobacter bradus* from subvision 1.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Researchers believe that an additional factor in the lack of understanding of carbon degradation by acidobacteria may stem from the present limited ability to provide adequate cultivation conditions.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] To study the natural behavior of these bacteria, they must grow and live in a controlled, observable environment.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] If such a habitat cannot be provided, recorded data cannot reliably report on the activity of the microbes in question.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Therefore, the inconsistencies between genome sequence based predictions and observed carbon processes may be explained by present study methods.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] There has been no clear evidence that Acidobacteriota are involved in nitrogen-cycle processes such as nitrification, denitrification, or nitrogen fixation.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] However, *Geothrix fermantans* was shown to be able to reduce nitrate and contained the norB gene.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] The NorB gene was also identified in *Koribacter verstailis* and *Solibacter usitatus*.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] In addition, the presence of the nirA gene has been observed in members of subdivision 1.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Additionally, to date, all genomes have been described to directly uptake ammonium via ammonium channel transporter family genes.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] Acidobacteriota can use both inorganic and organic nitrogen as their nitrogen sources.
[src:asgard-archaea/acidobacteriota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] An actin protein is the monomeric subunit of two types of filaments in cells: microfilaments, one of the three major components of the cytoskeleton, and thin filaments, part of the contractile apparatus in muscle cells.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] It can be present as either a free monomer called **G-actin** (globular) or as part of a linear polymer microfilament called **F-actin** (filamentous), both of which are essential for such important cellular functions as the mobility and contraction of cells during cell division.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Actin participates in many important cellular processes, including muscle contraction, cell motility, cell division and cytokinesis, vesicle and organelle movement, cell signaling, and the establishment and maintenance of cell junctions and cell shape.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Many of these processes are mediated by extensive and intimate interactions of actin with cellular membranes.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] In vertebrates, three main groups of actin isoforms, alpha, beta, and gamma have been identified.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The alpha actins, found in muscle tissues, are a major constituent of the contractile apparatus.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The beta and gamma actins coexist in most cell types as components of the cytoskeleton, and as mediators of internal cell motility.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] It is believed that the diverse range of structures formed by actin enabling it to fulfill such a large range of functions is regulated through the binding of tropomyosin along the filaments.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] A cell's ability to dynamically form microfilaments provides the scaffolding that allows it to rapidly remodel itself in response to its environment or to the organism's internal signals, for example, to increase cell membrane absorption or increase cell adhesion in order to form cell tissue.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Other enzymes or organelles such as cilia can be anchored to this scaffolding in order to control the deformation of the external cell membrane, which allows endocytosis and cytokinesis.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] It can also produce movement either by itself or with the help of molecular motors.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Actin therefore contributes to processes such as the intracellular transport of vesicles and organelles as well as muscular contraction and cellular migration.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] It therefore plays an important role in embryogenesis, the healing of wounds, and the invasivity of cancer cells.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The evolutionary origin of actin can be traced to prokaryotic cells, which have equivalent proteins.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Actin homologs from prokaryotes and archaea polymerize into different helical or linear filaments consisting of one or multiple strands.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] However the in-strand contacts and nucleotide binding sites are preserved in prokaryotes and in archaea.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Lastly, actin plays an important role in the control of gene expression.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] A large number of illnesses and diseases are caused by mutations in alleles of the genes that regulate the production of actin or of its associated proteins.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The production of actin is also key to the process of infection by some pathogenic microorganisms.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Mutations in the different genes that regulate actin production in humans can cause muscular diseases, variations in the size and function of the heart as well as deafness.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The make-up of the cytoskeleton is also related to the pathogenicity of intracellular bacteria and viruses, particularly in the processes related to evading the actions of the immune system.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Actin's primary role in the cell is to form linear polymers called microfilaments that serve various functions in the cell's structure, trafficking networks, migration, and replication.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The multifaceted role of actin relies on a few of the microfilaments' properties: First, the formation of actin filaments is reversible, and their function often involves undergoing rapid polymerization and depolymerization.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Second, microfilaments are polarized – i.e. the two ends of a filament are distinct from one another.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Third, actin filaments can bind to many other proteins, which together help modify and organize microfilaments for their diverse functions.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Actin is extremely abundant in most cells, comprising 1–5% of the total protein mass of most cells, and 10% of muscle cells.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The actin protein is found in both the cytoplasm and the cell nucleus.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Its location is regulated by cell membrane signal transduction pathways that integrate the stimuli that a cell receives stimulating the restructuring of the actin networks in response.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The role of actin as a regulator of chemical processes in the cell cytoplasm was proposed.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The cytoplasm is viscous, crowded, and heterogeneous, a dynamic complex, a gel-like substance that restricts free diffusion but is capable of managing a myriad of reactions at any moment.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The high capacity of the cytoplasm to perform complex chemical reactions can be explained by a two-phase system of organization, in which catalytic complexes are immobilized in the elastic solid phase (cytomatrix), thereby overcoming spatial hindrances and crowding .
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Nutrients and substrates can be delivered by liquid-phase (cytosol) flux, and the motor protein actin provides the driving force for cytomatrix mechanics.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Approximately 150 actin-binding and regulatory proteins fine-tune metabolic processes in the cytoplasm, thereby overcoming cytoplasmic viscosity.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The energy source for actin dynamics in normal physiological conditions is mitochondria.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] However, cancer cells, due to their high metabolic rate, require additional ATP, which can be supplied by glycolysis (the Warburg effect).
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] There are a number of different types of actin with slightly different structures and functions. α-actin is found exclusively in muscle fibres, while β- and γ-actin are found in other cells.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] As the latter types have a high turnover rate the majority of them are found outside permanent structures.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Actin's cytoskeleton is key to the processes of endocytosis, cytokinesis, determination of cell polarity and morphogenesis in yeasts.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] In addition to relying on actin, these processes involve 20 or 30 associated proteins, which all have a high degree of evolutionary conservation, along with many signalling molecules.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Together these elements allow a spatially and temporally modulated assembly that defines a cell's response to both internal and external stimuli.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Yeasts contain three main elements that are associated with actin: patches, cables, and rings.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Despite not being present for long, these structures are subject to a dynamic equilibrium due to continual polymerization and depolymerization.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Plant genome studies have revealed the existence of protein isovariants within the actin family of genes.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Within *Arabidopsis thaliana*, a model organism, there are ten types of actin, six profilins, and dozens of myosins.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] This diversity is explained by the evolutionary necessity of possessing variants that slightly differ in their temporal and spatial expression.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The majority of these proteins were jointly expressed in the tissue analysed.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Actin networks are distributed throughout the cytoplasm of cells that have been cultivated *in vitro*.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] There is a concentration of the network around the nucleus that is connected via spokes to the cellular cortex, this network is highly dynamic, with a continuous polymerization and depolymerization.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Even though the majority of plant cells have a cell wall that defines their morphology, their microfilaments can generate sufficient force to achieve a number of cellular activities, such as the cytoplasmic currents generated by the microfilaments and myosin.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Actin is also involved in the movement of organelles and in cellular morphogenesis, which involve cell division as well as the elongation and differentiation of the cell.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Nuclear actin was first noticed and described in 1977 by Clark and Merriam.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Authors describe a protein present in the nuclear fraction, obtained from *Xenopus laevis* oocytes, which shows the same features as skeletal muscle actin.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The actin sequence does not contain a nuclear localization signal.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The small size of actin (about 43 kDa) allows it to enter the nucleus by passive diffusion.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The import of actin into the nucleus (probably in a complex with cofilin) is facilitated by the import protein importin 9.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Low levels of actin in the nucleus seems to be important, because actin has two nuclear export signals (NES) in its sequence.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Microinjected actin is quickly removed from the nucleus to the cytoplasm.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Actin is exported at least in two ways, through exportin 1 and exportin 6.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Specific modifications, such as SUMOylation, allows for nuclear actin retention.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] A mutation preventing SUMOylation causes rapid export of beta actin from the nucleus.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Nuclear actin exists mainly as a monomer, but can also form dynamic oligomers and short polymers.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Nuclear actin organization varies in different cell types.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] For example, in *Xenopus* oocytes (with higher nuclear actin level in comparison to somatic cells) actin forms filaments, which stabilize nucleus architecture.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] These filaments can be observed under the microscope thanks to fluorophore-conjugated phalloidin staining.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] In somatic cell nuclei, however, actin filaments cannot be observed using this technique.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The DNase I inhibition assay, the only test which allows the quantification of the polymerized actin directly in biological samples, has revealed that endogenous nuclear actin indeed occurs mainly in a monomeric form.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Precisely controlled level of actin in the cell nucleus, lower than in the cytoplasm, prevents the formation of filaments.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The polymerization is also reduced by the limited access to actin monomers, which are bound in complexes with ABPs, mainly cofilin.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Different isoforms of actin are present in the cell nucleus.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The level of actin isoforms may change in response to stimulation of cell growth or arrest of proliferation and transcriptional activity.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Research on nuclear actin is focused on isoform beta.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] However the use of antibodies directed against different actin isoforms allows identifying not only the cytoplasmic beta in the cell nucleus, but also alpha- and gamma-actin in certain cell types.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The presence of different isoforms of actin may have a significant effect on its function in nuclear processes, as the level of individual isoforms can be controlled independently.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Functions of actin in the nucleus are associated with its ability to polymerize and interact with various ABPs and with structural elements of the nucleus.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Due to its ability to undergo conformational changes and interaction with many proteins, actin acts as a regulator of formation and activity of protein complexes such as transcriptional complex.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Actin is also involved in cell movement.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Several different types of protrusions mediated directly or indirectly by actin are involved in cell migration in different ways, with the most important ones being lamellipodia, filopodia, invadopodia and blebs.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] A meshwork of actin filaments marks the forward edge of a moving cell, and the polymerization of new actin filaments pushes the cell membrane forward in protrusions called lamellipodia.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] These membrane protrusions then attach to the substrate, forming structures known as focal adhesions that connect to the actin network.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Once attached, the rear of the cell body contracts squeezing its contents forward past the adhesion point.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Once the adhesion point has moved to the rear of the cell, the cell disassembles it, allowing the rear of the cell to move forward.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Filopodia are thin extensions of the plasma membrane that contain parallel bundles of actin filaments, in contrast to the branched actin structures of lamellipodia.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] They serve an exploratory role, being used by cells to probe their environment.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] While the presence of filopodia is linked to enhanced cell migration, they are not directly involved in cell body displacement.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Invadopodia are actin-driven membrane protrusions that help to degrade the extracellular matrix.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] They are used by cancer cells for cell invasion, particularly to help them cross the basement membrane.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The matrix degradation takes place by transporting vesicles containing matrix-degrading proteins to the invadopodia where the proteins are released via exocytosis.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Blebs are spherical membrane protrusions that are involved in both apoptosis and cell movement.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The driving force behind bleb extension is hydrostatic pressure, rather than actin filament elongation which drives lamellipodia, filopodia and invadopodia extension.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Blebs are formed by actomyosin contraction, which causes the delamination of the plasma membrane from the actin cortex or a focal rupture of the actin cortex.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] They are then stabilized via actin cortex reassembly and finally retracted via actomyosin contraction.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] In migrating cells a front-rear polarity is established, with bleb formation restricted to the leading edge, allowing for directed movement.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] In addition to the physical force generated by actin polymerization, microfilaments facilitate the movement of various intracellular components by serving as the roadway along which a family of motor proteins called myosins travel.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Actin plays a particularly prominent role in muscle cells, which consist largely of repeated bundles of actin and myosin II.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Each repeated unit – called a sarcomere – consists of two sets of oppositely oriented F-actin strands ("thin filaments"), interlaced with bundles of myosin ("thick filaments").
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The two sets of actin strands are oriented with their (+) ends embedded in either end of the sarcomere in delimiting structures called Z-disks.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The myosin fibrils are in the middle between the sets of actin filaments, with strands facing in both directions.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] When the muscle contracts, the myosin threads move along the actin filaments towards the (+) end, pulling the ends of the sarcomere together and shortening it by around 70% of its length.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] In order to move along the actin thread, myosin must hydrolyze ATP; thus ATP serves as the energy source for muscle contraction.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] At times of rest, the proteins tropomyosin and troponin bind to the actin filaments, preventing the attachment of myosin.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] When an activation signal (i.e. an action potential) arrives at the muscle fiber, it triggers the release of Ca2+ from the sarcoplasmic reticulum into the cytosol.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The resulting spike in cytosolic calcium rapidly releases tropomyosin and troponin from the actin thread, allowing myosin to bind, and muscle contraction to begin.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] In the final stages of cell division, many cells form a ring of actin at the cell's midpoint.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] This ring, aptly called the "contractile ring", uses a similar mechanism as muscle fibers where myosin II pulls along the actin ring, causing it to contract.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] This contraction cleaves the parent cell into two, completing cytokinesis.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The contractile ring is composed of actin, myosin, anillin, and α-actinin.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] In the fission yeast *Schizosaccharomyces pombe*, actin is actively formed in the constricting ring with the participation of Arp3, the formin Cdc12, profilin, and WASp, along with preformed microfilaments.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Once the ring has been constructed the structure is maintained by a continual assembly and disassembly that, aided by the Arp2/3 complex and formins, is key to one of the central processes of cytokinesis.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Actin-myosin pairs can also participate in the trafficking of various membrane vesicles and organelles within the cell.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Myosin V is activated by binding to various cargo receptors on organelles, and then moves along an actin filament towards the (+) end, pulling its cargo along with it.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] These nonconventional myosins use ATP hydrolysis to transport cargo, such as vesicles and organelles, in a directed fashion much faster than diffusion.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Myosin V walks towards the barbed end of actin filaments, while myosin VI walks toward the pointed end.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Most actin filaments are arranged with the barbed end toward the cellular membrane and the pointed end toward the cellular interior.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] This arrangement allows myosin V to be an effective motor for the export of cargos, and myosin VI to be an effective motor for import.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The traditional image of actin's function relates it to the maintenance of the cytoskeleton and, therefore, the organization and movement of organelles, as well as the determination of a cell's shape.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] However, actin has a wider role in eukaryotic cell physiology, in addition to similar functions in prokaryotes.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Monomeric actin, or G-actin, has a globular structure consisting of two lobes separated by a deep cleft.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The bottom of the cleft represents the "ATPase fold", a structure conserved among ATP and GTP-binding proteins that binds to a magnesium ion and a molecule of ATP.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Binding of ATP or ADP is required to stabilize each actin monomer; without one of these molecules bound, actin quickly becomes denatured.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The X-ray crystallography model of actin that was produced by Kabsch from the striated muscle tissue of rabbits is the most commonly used in structural studies as it was the first to be purified.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The G-actin crystallized by Kabsch is approximately 67 x 40 x 37 Å in size, has a molecular mass of 41,785 Da and an estimated isoelectric point of 4.8.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Elzinga and co-workers first determined the complete peptide sequence for this type of actin in 1973, with later work by the same author adding further detail to the model.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Its N-terminus is highly acidic and starts with an acetyled aspartate in its amino group, while its C-terminus is alkaline and is formed by a phenylalanine preceded by a cysteine, which has a degree of functional importance.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Both extremes are in close proximity within the I-subdomain.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] An anomalous *N*τ-methylhistidine is located at position 73.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The tertiary structure is formed by two domains known as the large and the small, which are separated by a cleft centred around the location of the bond with ATP-ADP+Pi.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Below this there is a deeper notch called a "groove".
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] In the native state, despite their names, both have a comparable depth.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The normal convention in topological studies means that a protein is shown with the biggest domain on the left-hand side and the smallest domain on the right-hand side.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] In this position the smaller domain is in turn divided into two: subdomain I (lower position, residues 1–32, 70–144, and 338–374) and subdomain II (upper position, residues 33–69).
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The larger domain is also divided in two: subdomain III (lower, residues 145–180 and 270–337) and subdomain IV (higher, residues 181–269).
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The exposed areas of subdomains I and III are referred to as the "barbed" ends, while the exposed areas of domains II and IV are termed the "pointed" ends.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] This nomenclature refers to the fact that, due to the small mass of subdomain II actin is polar; the importance of this will be discussed below in the discussion on assembly dynamics.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Some authors call the subdomains Ia, Ib, IIa, and IIb, respectively.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The most notable supersecondary structure is a five chain beta sheet that is composed of a β-meander and a β-α-β clockwise unit.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] It is present in both domains suggesting that the protein arose from gene duplication.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Under various conditions, G-actin molecules polymerize into longer threads called "filamentous-" or "F-actin".
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] These F-actin threads are typically composed of two helical strands of actin wound around each other, forming a 7 to 9 nanometer wide helix that repeats every 72 nanometers (or every 14 G-actin subunits).
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] In F-actin threads, G-actin molecules are all oriented in the same direction.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The two ends of the F-actin thread are distinct from one another.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] At one end – designated the (−) end – the ATP-binding cleft of the terminal actin molecule is facing outward.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] At the opposite end – designated (+) – the ATP-binding cleft is buried in the filament, contacting the neighboring actin molecule.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] As F-actin threads grow, new molecules tend to join at the (+) end of an existing F-actin strand.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Conversely, threads tend to shrink by shedding actin monomers from the strand's (−) end.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Some proteins, such as cofilin appear to increase the angle of turn, but again this could be interpreted as the establishment of different structural states.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] These could be important in the polymerization process.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] There is less agreement regarding measurements of the turn radius and filament thickness: while the first models assigned a length of 25 Å, current X-ray diffraction data, backed up by cryo-electron microscopy suggests a length of 23.7 Å.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] These studies have shown the precise contact points between monomers.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Some are formed with units of the same chain, between the "barbed" end on one monomer and the "pointed" end of the next one.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] While the monomers in adjacent chains make lateral contact through projections from subdomain IV, with the most important projections being those formed by the C-terminus and the hydrophobic link formed by three bodies involving residues 39–42, 201–203, and 286.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] This model suggests that a filament is formed by monomers in a "sheet" formation, in which the subdomains turn about themselves, this form is also found in the bacterial actin homologue MreB.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The terms "pointed" and "barbed" referring to the two ends of the microfilaments derive from their appearance under transmission electron microscopy when samples are examined following a preparation technique called "decoration".
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] This method consists of the addition of myosin S1 fragments to tissue that has been fixed with tannic acid.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] This myosin forms polar bonds with actin monomers, giving rise to a configuration that looks like arrows with feather fletchings along its shaft, where the shaft is the actin and the fletchings are the myosin.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Following this logic, the end of the microfilament that does not have any protruding myosin is called the point of the arrow (− end) and the other end is called the barbed end (+ end).
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] A S1 fragment is composed of the head and neck domains of myosin II.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Under physiological conditions, G-actin (the monomer form) is transformed to F-actin (the polymer form) by ATP, where the role of ATP is essential.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The helical F-actin filament found in muscles also contains a tropomyosin molecule, which is a 40 nanometre long protein that is wrapped around the F-actin helix.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] During the resting phase the tropomyosin covers the actin's active sites so that the actin-myosin interaction cannot take place and produce muscular contraction.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] There are other protein molecules bound to the tropomyosin thread, these are the troponins that have three polymers: troponin I, troponin T, and troponin C.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Unlike other polymers, such as DNA, whose constituent elements are bound together with covalent bonds, the monomers of actin filaments are assembled by weaker bonds.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The lateral bonds with neighbouring monomers resolve this anomaly, which in theory should weaken the structure as they can be broken by thermal agitation.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] In addition, the weak bonds give the advantage that the filament ends can easily release or incorporate monomers.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] This means that the filaments can be rapidly remodelled and can change cellular structure in response to an environmental stimulus.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Which, along with the biochemical mechanism by which it is brought about is known as the "assembly dynamic".
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Actin can spontaneously acquire a large part of its tertiary structure.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] However, the way it acquires its fully functional form from its newly synthesized native form is special and almost unique in protein chemistry.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The reason for this special route could be the need to avoid the presence of incorrectly folded actin monomers, which could be toxic as they can act as inefficient polymerization terminators.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Nevertheless, it is key to establishing the stability of the cytoskeleton, and additionally, it is an essential process for coordinating the cell cycle.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] CCT is required in order to ensure that folding takes place correctly.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] CCT is a group II chaperonin, a large protein complex that assists in the folding of other proteins.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] CCT is formed of a double ring of eight different subunits (hetero-octameric) and it differs from group I chaperonins like GroEL, which is found in Eubacteria and in eukaryotic organelles, as it does not require a co-chaperone to act as a lid over the central catalytic cavity.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Substrates bind to CCT through specific domains.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] It was initially thought that it only bound with actin and tubulin, although recent immunoprecipitation studies have shown that it interacts with a large number of polypeptides, which possibly function as substrates.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] It acts through ATP-dependent conformational changes that on occasion require several rounds of liberation and catalysis in order to complete a reaction.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] In order to successfully complete their folding, both actin and tubulin need to interact with another protein called prefoldin, which is a heterohexameric complex (formed by six distinct subunits), in an interaction that is so specific that the molecules have coevolved.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Actin forms a complex with prefoldin while it is still being formed, when it is approximately 145 amino acids long, specifically those at the N-terminal.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Different recognition sub-units are used for actin or tubulin although there is some overlap.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] In actin the subunits that bind with prefoldin are probably PFD3 and PFD4, which bind in two places one between residues 60–79 and the other between residues 170–198.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The actin is recognized, loaded, and delivered to the cytosolic chaperonin (CCT) in an open conformation by the inner end of prefoldin's "tentacles" (see the image and note).
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The contact when actin is delivered is so brief that a tertiary complex is not formed, immediately freeing the prefoldin.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The CCT then causes actin's sequential folding by forming bonds with its subunits rather than simply enclosing it in its cavity.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] This is why it possesses specific recognition areas in its apical β-domain.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The first stage in the folding consists of the recognition of residues 245–249.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Next, other determinants establish contact.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Both actin and tubulin bind to CCT in open conformations in the absence of ATP.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] In actin's case, two subunits are bound during each conformational change, whereas for tubulin binding takes place with four subunits.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Actin has specific binding sequences, which interact with the δ and β-CCT subunits or with δ-CCT and ε-CCT.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] After AMP-PNP is bound to CCT the substrates move within the chaperonin's cavity.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] It also seems that in the case of actin, the CAP protein is required as a possible cofactor in actin's final folding states.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The exact manner by which this process is regulated is still not fully understood, but it is known that the protein PhLP3 (a protein similar to phosducin) inhibits its activity through the formation of a tertiary complex.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Actin is an ATPase, which means that it is an enzyme that hydrolyzes ATP.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] This group of enzymes is characterised by their slow reaction rates.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] It is known that this ATPase is "active", that is, its speed increases by some 40,000 times when the actin forms part of a filament.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] A reference value for this rate of hydrolysis under ideal conditions is around 0.3 s−1.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Then, the Pi remains bound to the actin next to the ADP for a long time, until it is cooperatively liberated from the interior of the filament.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The exact molecular details of the catalytic mechanism are still not fully understood.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Although there is much debate on this issue, it seems certain that a "closed" conformation is required for the hydrolysis of ATP, and it is thought that the residues that are involved in the process move to the appropriate distance.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The glutamic acid Glu137 is one of the key residues, which is located in subdomain 1.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Its function is to bind the water molecule that produces a nucleophilic attack on the ATP's γ-phosphate bond, while the nucleotide is strongly bound to subdomains 3 and 4.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The slowness of the catalytic process is due to the large distance and skewed position of the water molecule in relation to the reactant.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] It is highly likely that the conformational change produced by the rotation of the domains between actin's G and F forms moves the Glu137 closer allowing its hydrolysis.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] This model suggests that the polymerization and ATPase's function would be decoupled straight away.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The "open" to "closed" transformation between G and F forms and its implications on the relative motion of several key residues and the formation of water wires have been characterized in molecular dynamics and QM/MM simulations.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Actin filaments are often rapidly assembled and disassembled, allowing them to generate force and support cell movement.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Assembly classically occurs in three steps.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] First, the "nucleation phase", in which two to three G-actin molecules slowly join to form a small oligomer that will nucleate further growth.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Second, the "elongation phase", when the actin filament rapidly grows by the addition of many actin molecules to both ends.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] As the filament grows, actin molecules are added to the (+) end of the filament around 10 times faster than to the (−) end, and so filaments tend to primarily grow at the (+) end.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Third, the "steady-state phase", where an equillibrium is reached as actin molecules join and leave the filament at the same rate, maintaining the filament's length.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] While the filament's length remains constant in the steady-state phase, new molecules are constantly being added to the (+) end and falling off the (−) end, a phenomenon called "treadmilling" as a given actin molecule would appear to move along the strand.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] In isolation, whether a filament will grow or shrink, and how quickly, are determined by the concentration of G-actin around the filament; however, in cells, the dynamics of actin filaments are heavily influenced by various actin-binding proteins.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The actin cytoskeleton *in vivo* is not exclusively composed of actin, other proteins are required for its formation, continuance, and function.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] These proteins are called actin-binding proteins and they are involved in actin's polymerization, depolymerization, stability, and organisation.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The diversity of these proteins is such that actin is thought to be the protein that takes part in the greatest number of protein-protein interactions.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The nucleation of new actin filaments – the rate-limiting step in actin polymerization – is aided by actin-nucleating proteins such as formins (like formin-2) and the Arp2/3 complex.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Formins help to nucleate long actin filaments.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] They bind two free actin-ATP molecules, bringing them together.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Then as the filament begins to grow, formin moves along the (+) end of the growing filament, all the while recruiting actin-binding proteins that promote filament growth, and excluding capping proteins that would block filament extension.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Branches in actin filaments are typically nucleated by the Arp2/3 complex in concert with nucleation promoting factors.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Nucleation promoting factors bind two free G-actin molecules, then recruit and activate the Arp2/3 complex.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The activated Arp2/3 complex attaches to an existing actin filament, and uses the two bound G-actin molecules to nucleate a new actin filament branching off of the old one at a 70° angle.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] As filaments grow, the pool of available G-actin molecules is managed by G-actin-binding proteins such as profilin and thymosin β-4.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Profilin ensures a supply of available actin-ATP by binding to ADP-bound G-actin and promoting the exchange of ADP for ATP.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Profilin's binding to the actin molecule physically blocks its addition to a filament's (−) end, but permits it to join the (+) end.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Once the actin-ATP has joined the filament, profilin releases it.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] As formins promote the nucleation and extension of new actin filaments, they recruit profilin to the area, increasing the local concentration of actin-ATP to boost filament growth.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] In contrast, thymosin β-4 binds and sequesters actin-ATP, preventing it from joining a microfilament.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Once an actin fiber is established, the dynamics of its growth or collapse are influenced by numerous proteins.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Existing strands can be interrupted by filament cleaving proteins, such as cofilin and gelsolin.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Cofilin binds along two actin-ADP molecules in a filament, forcing a movement that destabilizes the filament and causes it to break.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Gelsolin inserts itself between actin molecules in a filament, disrupting the filament.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] After the filament breaks, gelsolin remains attached to the new (+) end, preventing it from growing, thus forcing its disassembly.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Other proteins bind to the ends of actin filaments, stabilizing them.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] These are called "capping proteins" and include CapZ and tropomodulin.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] CapZ binds the (+) end of a filament, preventing further addition or loss of actin from that end.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Tropomodulin binds to a filament's (−) end, again preventing addition or loss of molecule's at that end.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Tropomodulin is typically found in cells that require extremely stable actin filaments, such as those in muscle and red blood cells.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] These actin binding proteins are typically regulated by various cellular signals to control actin assembly dynamics in different cellular locations.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Formins, for example, are typically folded in an inactive conformation until they're activated by the binding of the small GTPase Rho.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Actin branching at the cell membrane is important for cell movement, and so the plasma membrane lipid PIP2 activates the nucleation promoting factor WASp and inhibits CapZ.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] WASp is also activated by the small GTPase Cdc42, while another nucleation promoting factor WAVE is activated by the GTPase Rac1.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Although most yeasts have only a single actin gene, higher eukaryotes, in general, express several isoforms of actin encoded by a family of related genes.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Mammals have at least six actin isoforms coded by separate genes, which are divided into three classes – alpha, beta, and gamma – according to their isoelectric points.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] In general, alpha actins are found in muscle (α-skeletal, α-aortic smooth, α-cardiac), whereas beta and gamma isoforms are prominent in non-muscle cells (β-cytoplasmic, γ1-cytoplasmic, γ2-enteric smooth).
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Although the amino acid sequences and *in vitro* properties of the isoforms are highly similar, these isoforms cannot completely substitute for one another *in vivo*.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] Plants contains more than 60 actin genes and pseudogenes.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The typical actin gene has an approximately 100-nucleotide 5' UTR, a 1200-nucleotide translated region, and a 200-nucleotide 3' UTR.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The majority of actin genes are interrupted by introns, with up to six introns in any of 19 well-characterised locations.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p01] The high conservation of the family makes actin the favoured model for studies comparing the introns-early and introns-late models of intron evolution.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Actin and closely related proteins are present in all organisms, suggesting the common ancestor of all life on Earth had actin.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Actin is one of the most conserved proteins throughout the evolution of eukaryotes.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The sequences of actin proteins from animals and amoebae are 80% identical despite being separated by approximately one billion years of evolution.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Many unicellular eukaryotes have a single actin gene, while multicellular eukaryotes often have several closely related genes that serve specialized functions.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Humans have six; plants have 10 or more.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] In addition to actin, eukaryotes have a large family of actin-related proteins, or "Arps", that share a common ancestor with actin and are called Arp1–Arp11, with Arp1 the most closely related to actin, and Arp11 the least.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Bacteria encode three types of actin: MreB influences cell shape, FtsA cell division, and ParM separation of large plasmids.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Some archaea have a bacteria-like MreB gene, while others have an actin gene that more closely resembles eukaryote actin.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The eukaryotic cytoskeleton of organisms among all taxonomic groups have similar components to actin and tubulin.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] For example, the protein that is coded by the *ACTG2* gene in humans is completely equivalent to the homologues present in rats and mice, even though at a nucleotide level the similarity decreases to 92%.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] However, there are major differences with the equivalents in prokaryotes (FtsZ and MreB), where the similarity between nucleotide sequences is between 40 and 50% among different bacteria and archaea species.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Some authors suggest that the ancestral protein that gave rise to the model eukaryotic actin resembles the proteins present in modern bacterial cytoskeletons.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Some authors point out that the behaviour of actin, tubulin, and histone, a protein involved in the stabilization and regulation of DNA, are similar in their ability to bind nucleotides and in their ability of take advantage of Brownian motion.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] It has also been suggested that they all have a common ancestor.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Therefore, evolutionary processes resulted in the diversification of ancestral proteins into the varieties present today, conserving, among others, actins as efficient molecules that were able to tackle essential ancestral biological processes, such as endocytosis.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The Arp2/3 complex is widely found in all eukaryotic organisms.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The bacterial cytoskeleton contains proteins that are highly similar to actin monomers and polymers.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The bacterial protein MreB polymerizes into thin non-helical filaments and occasionally into helical structures similar to F-actin.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Furthermore, its crystalline structure is very similar to that of G-actin (in terms of its three-dimensional conformation), there are even similarities between the MreB protofilaments and F-actin.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The bacterial cytoskeleton also contains the FtsZ proteins, which are similar to tubulin.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Bacteria therefore possess a cytoskeleton with homologous elements to actin (for example, MreB, AlfA, ParM, FtsA, and MamK), even though the amino acid sequence of these proteins diverges from that present in animal cells.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] However, such proteins have a high degree of structural similarity to eukaryotic actin.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The highly dynamic microfilaments formed by the aggregation of MreB and ParM are essential to cell viability and they are involved in cell morphogenesis, chromosome segregation, and cell polarity.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] ParM is an actin homologue that is coded in a plasmid and it is involved in the regulation of plasmid DNA.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] ParMs from different bacterial plasmids can form astonishingly diverse helical structures comprising two or four strands to maintain faithful plasmid inheritance.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] In archaea the homologue Ta0583 is even more similar to the eukaryotic actins.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The majority of mammals possess six different actin genes.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Of these, two code for the cytoskeleton (*ACTB* and *ACTG1*) while the other four are involved in skeletal striated muscle (*ACTA1*), smooth muscle tissue (*ACTA2*), intestinal muscles (*ACTG2*) and cardiac muscle (*ACTC1*).
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The actin in the cytoskeleton is involved in the pathogenic mechanisms of many infectious agents, including HIV.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The vast majority of the mutations that affect actin are point mutations that have a dominant effect, with the exception of six mutations involved in nemaline myopathy.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] This is because in many cases the mutant of the actin monomer acts as a "cap" by preventing the elongation of F-actin.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The mutation alters the structure and function of skeletal muscles producing one of three forms of myopathy: type 3 nemaline myopathy, congenital myopathy with an excess of thin myofilaments (CM) and congenital myopathy with fibre type disproportion (CMFTD).
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Mutations have also been found that produce core myopathies.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Although their phenotypes are similar, in addition to typical nemaline myopathy some specialists distinguish another type of myopathy called actinic nemaline myopathy.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] In the former, clumps of actin form instead of the typical rods.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] It is important to state that a patient can show more than one of these phenotypes in a biopsy.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The most common symptoms consist of a typical facial morphology (myopathic facies), muscular weakness, a delay in motor development and respiratory difficulties.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The course of the illness, its gravity, and the age at which it appears are all variable and overlapping forms of myopathy are also found.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] A symptom of nemaline myopathy is that "nemaline rods" appear in differing places in type 1 muscle fibres.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] These rods are non-pathognomonic structures that have a similar composition to the Z disks found in the sarcomere.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The pathogenesis of this myopathy is very varied.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Many mutations occur in the region of actin's indentation near to its nucleotide binding sites, while others occur in Domain 2, or in the areas where interaction occurs with associated proteins.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] This goes some way to explain the great variety of clumps that form in these cases, such as Nemaline or Intranuclear Bodies or Zebra Bodies.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Changes in actin's folding occur in nemaline myopathy as well as changes in its aggregation and there are also changes in the expression of other associated proteins.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] In some variants where intranuclear bodies are found the changes in the folding masks the nucleus's protein exportation signal so that the accumulation of actin's mutated form occurs in the cell nucleus.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] On the other hand, it appears that mutations to *ACTA1* that give rise to a CFTDM have a greater effect on sarcomeric function than on its structure.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Recent investigations have tried to understand this apparent paradox, which suggests there is no clear correlation between the number of rods and muscular weakness.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] It appears that some mutations are able to induce a greater apoptosis rate in type II muscular fibres.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The *ACTC1* gene codes for the α-actin isoform present in heart muscle.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] It was first sequenced by Hamada and co-workers in 1982, when it was found that it is interrupted by five introns.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] It was the first of the six genes where alleles were found that were implicated in pathological processes.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] A number of structural disorders associated with point mutations of this gene have been described that cause malfunctioning of the heart, such as Type 1R dilated cardiomyopathy and Type 11 hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Certain defects of the atrial septum have been described recently that could also be related to these mutations.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Two cases of dilated cardiomyopathy have been studied involving a substitution of highly conserved amino acids belonging to the protein domains that bind and intersperse with the Z discs.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] This has led to the theory that the dilation is produced by a defect in the transmission of contractile force in the myocytes.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The mutations in ACTC1 are responsible for at least 5% of hypertrophic cardiomyopathies.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Recent studies have discovered ACTC1 mutations that are implicated in two other pathological processes: Infantile idiopathic restrictive cardiomyopathy, and noncompaction of the left ventricular myocardium.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The *ACTG1* locus codes for the cytosolic γ-actin protein that is responsible for the formation of cytoskeletal microfilaments.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] It contains six exons, giving rise to 22 different mRNAs, which produce four complete isoforms whose form of expression is probably dependent on the type of tissue they are found in.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] It also has two different DNA promoters.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] It has been noted that the sequences translated from this locus and from that of β-actin are very similar to the predicted ones, suggesting a common ancestral sequence that suffered duplication and genetic conversion.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] In terms of pathology, it has been associated with processes such as amyloidosis, retinitis pigmentosa, infection mechanisms, kidney diseases, and various types of congenital hearing loss.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Six autosomal-dominant point mutations in the sequence have been found to cause various types of hearing loss, particularly sensorineural hearing loss linked to the DFNA 20/26 locus.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] It seems that they affect the stereocilia of the ciliated cells present in the inner ear's Organ of Corti. β-actin is the most abundant protein found in human tissue, but it is not very abundant in ciliated cells, which explains the location of the pathology.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] On the other hand, it appears that the majority of these mutations affect the areas involved in linking with other proteins, particularly actomyosin.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Some experiments have suggested that the pathological mechanism for this type of hearing loss relates to the F-actin in the mutations being more sensitive to cofilin than normal.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] However, although there is no record of any case, it is known that γ-actin is also expressed in skeletal muscles, and although it is present in small quantities, model organisms have shown that its absence can give rise to myopathies.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Some infectious agents use actin, especially cytoplasmic actin, in their life cycle.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] In addition to the previously cited example, actin polymerization is stimulated in the initial steps of the internalization of some viruses, notably HIV, by, for example, inactivating the cofilin complex.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The role that actin plays in the invasion process of cancer cells has still not been determined.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] In conditions of high lipoperoxidation, actin has been shown to be post-translationally modified by the lipoperoxidation product 4-hydroxynonenal (4-HNE).
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] This modification prevents the remodelling of the actin cytoskeleton, which is essential for cell motility.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Additionally, another functional protein, coronin-1A, which stabilizes F-actin filaments, is also covalently modified by 4-HNE.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Actin is used in scientific and technological laboratories as a track for molecular motors such as myosin (either in muscle tissue or outside it) and as a necessary component for cellular functioning.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] It can also be used as a diagnostic tool, as several of its anomalous variants are related to the appearance of specific pathologies.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The use of actin as an internal control is based on the assumption that its expression is practically constant and independent of experimental conditions.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] By comparing the expression of the gene of interest to that of the actin, it is possible to obtain a relative quantity that can be compared between different experiments, whenever the expression of the latter is constant.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] It is worth pointing out that actin does not always have the desired stability in its gene expression.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Actin was first observed experimentally in 1887 by W.D.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Halliburton, who extracted a protein from muscle that 'coagulated' preparations of myosin that he called "myosin-ferment".
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] However, Halliburton was unable to further refine his findings, and the discovery of actin is credited instead to Brunó Ferenc Straub, a young biochemist working in Albert Szent-Györgyi's laboratory at the Institute of Medical Chemistry at the University of Szeged, Hungary.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Following up on the discovery of Ilona Banga & Szent-Györgyi in 1941 that the coagulation only occurs in some myosin extractions and was reversed upon the addition of ATP, Straub identified and purified actin from those myosin preparations that did coagulate.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Building on Banga's original extraction method, he developed a novel technique for extracting muscle protein that allowed him to isolate substantial amounts of relatively pure actin, published in 1942.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Straub's method is essentially the same as that used in laboratories today.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Since Straub's protein was necessary to activate the coagulation of myosin, it was dubbed *actin*.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Realizing that Banga's coagulating myosin preparations contained actin as well, Szent-Györgyi called the mixture of both proteins actomyosin.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The hostilities of World War II meant Szent-Gyorgyi was unable to publish his lab's work in Western scientific journals.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Actin therefore only became well known in the West in 1945, when their paper was published as a supplement to the *Acta Physiologica Scandinavica*.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Straub continued to work on actin, and in 1950 reported that actin contains bound ATP and that, during polymerization of the protein into microfilaments, the nucleotide is hydrolyzed to ADP and inorganic phosphate (which remain bound to the microfilament).
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Straub suggested that the transformation of ATP-bound actin to ADP-bound actin played a role in muscular contraction.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] In fact, this is true only in smooth muscle, and was not supported through experimentation until 2001.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The amino acid sequencing of actin was completed by M.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The crystal structure of G-actin was solved in 1990 by Kabsch and colleagues.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] In the same year, a model for F-actin was proposed by Holmes and colleagues following experiments using co-crystallization with different proteins.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The procedure of co-crystallization with different proteins was used repeatedly during the following years, until in 2001 the isolated protein was crystallized along with ADP.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] However, there is still no high-resolution X-ray structure of F-actin.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] The crystallization of G-actin was possible due to the use of a rhodamine conjugate that impedes polymerization by blocking the amino acid cys-374.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Christine Oriol-Audit died in the same year that actin was first crystallized but she was the researcher that in 1977 first crystallized actin in the absence of Actin Binding Proteins (ABPs).
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] However, the resulting crystals were too small for the available technology of the time.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Although no high-resolution model of actin's filamentous form currently exists, in 2008 Sawaya's team were able to produce a more exact model of its structure based on multiple crystals of actin dimers that bind in different places.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] This model has subsequently been further refined by Sawaya and Lorenz.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Other approaches such as the use of cryo-electron microscopy and synchrotron radiation have recently allowed increasing resolution and better understanding of the nature of the interactions and conformational changes implicated in the formation of actin filaments.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] A number of natural toxins that interfere with actin's dynamics are widely used in research to study actin's role in biology.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Latrunculin – a toxin produced by sponges – binds to G-actin preventing it from joining microfilaments.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Cytochalasin D – produced by certain fungi – serves as a capping factor, binding to the (+) end of a filament and preventing further addition of actin molecules.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] In contrast, the sponge toxin jasplakinolide promotes the nucleation of new actin filaments by binding and stabilizing pairs of actin molecules.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Phalloidin – from the "death cap" mushroom *Amanita phalloides* – binds to adjacent actin molecules within the F-actin filament, stabilizing the filament and preventing its depolymerization.
[src:asgard-archaea/actin-p02] Phalloidin is often labelled with fluorescent dyes to visualize actin filaments by fluorescence microscopy.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] The **Actinomycetota** (previously known as **"Actinobacteria"**) are a diverse phylum of Gram-positive bacteria with high guanine-cytosine content (GC content or G+C content).
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] They are of great importance to land flora because of their contributions to soil systems.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] In soil, they help decompose organic matter of dead organisms so the molecules can be taken up anew by plants.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] While this role is also played by fungi, actinomycetota are much smaller and likely do not occupy the same ecological niche.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] In this role, the colonies often grow extensive mycelia, as fungi do, and the name of an important order of the phylum, Actinomycetales (the actinomycetes), reflects that they were long believed to be fungi.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] Some soil actinomycetota (such as *Frankia*) live symbiotically with the plants whose roots pervade the soil, fixing nitrogen for the plants in exchange for access to some of the plant's saccharides.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] Other species, such as many members of the genus *Mycobacterium*, are important pathogens.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] Beyond the great interest in Actinomycetota for their soil role, much is yet to be learned about them.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] Although currently understood primarily as soil bacteria, they might be more abundant in fresh waters.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota is one of the dominant bacterial phyla and contains one of the largest of bacterial genera: *Streptomyces*.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] *Streptomyces* and other actinomycetota are major contributors to biological buffering of soils.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] They are also the source of many antibiotics.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] Bacteria of the Actinomycetota genus *Bifidobacterium* are the most common in the microbiome of human infants.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] Although adults have fewer bifidobacteria, intestinal bifidobacteria help maintain the mucosal barrier and reduce lipopolysaccharides in the intestine.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] Although some of the largest and most complex bacterial cells belong to the Actinomycetota, the group of marine Actinomarinales has been described as possessing the smallest free-living prokaryotic cells.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] Some Siberian or Antarctic biofilms of these bacteria are said to have the longest lifespan of any organism on Earth, frozen in permafrost at around half a million years ago.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] Most actinomycetota of medical or economic significance are in class Actinomycetia, and belong to the order Actinomycetales.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] While many of these cause disease in humans, *Streptomyces* is notable as a source of antibiotics.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] Of those actinomycetota not in the Actinomycetales, *Gardnerella* is one of the most researched.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] Classification of *Gardnerella* is controversial, and MeSH catalogues it as both a Gram-positive and Gram-negative organism.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota-derived antibiotics that are important in medicine include aminoglycosides, anthracyclines, chloramphenicol, macrolides, tetracyclines, etc.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota have high guanine and cytosine content in their DNA.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] The GC content of actinomycetota can be as high as 70%, though some may have a low GC content.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] Analysis of glutamine synthetase sequence has been suggested for phylogenetic analysis of the Actinomycetota.
[src:asgard-archaea/actinomycetota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:asgard-archaea/aerophobota] The classification is based on genomic and metagenomic data without cultured isolates, and the name is not yet validly published under formal bacterial nomenclature.
[src:asgard-archaea/aerophobota] Aerophobetes are abundant in hydrate-containing, silty sediment layers beneath the ocean floor and thrive in anoxic (oxygen-free) conditions.
[src:asgard-archaea/aerophobota] Genetic analyses suggest they ferment organic matter, producing hydrogen and acetate, which can then be used by syntrophic methanogenic archaea to generate methane.
[src:asgard-archaea/aerophobota] These metabolic interactions indicate Aerophobota's likely contribution to methane formation and carbon cycling in deep-sea ecosystems.
[src:asgard-archaea/aerophobota] Research into Aerophobota and its functional roles is of interest because methane is a potent greenhouse gas.
[src:asgard-archaea/aerophobota] Understanding these microbes could inform strategies for mitigating methane emissions from seafloor hydrates.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] The Alphaproteobacteria are a diverse taxon and comprise several phototrophic genera, several genera metabolising C1-compounds (e.g.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] *Methylobacterium* spp.), symbionts of plants (e.g.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] *Rhizobium* spp.), endosymbionts of arthropods (*Wolbachia*) and intracellular pathogens (e.g.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] Moreover, the class is sister to the protomitochondrion, the bacterium that was engulfed by the eukaryotic ancestor and gave rise to the mitochondria, which are organelles in eukaryotic cells (see Endosymbiotic theory).
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] A species of technological interest is *Agrobacterium tumefaciens* (also called *Rhizobium radiobacter*): scientists often use this species to transfer foreign DNA into plant genomes.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] Aerobic anoxygenic phototrophic bacteria, such as *Pelagibacter ubique*, are alphaproteobacteria that are a widely distributed and may constitute over 10% of the open ocean microbial community.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] Several points of disagreement muddy the recovery of the phylogenetic relationships among the Alphaproteobacteria clades from the genomic data.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] One such point centers on the placement of the Pelagibacterales stemming from the large differences in gene content (*e.g.* genome streamlining in *Pelagibacter ubique*) and GC-content between members of several orders.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] Specifically, certain species within Pelagibacterales, Rickettsiales, and Holosporales possess AT-rich genomes, containing higher-assayed concentrations of adenine-thymine (AT) pairs than guanine-cytosine (GC) base pairs.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] While it could be a case of convergent evolution resulting in an artefactual clustering, several studies disagree and no consensus has been reached.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] Furthermore, the GC-content of ribosomal RNA, the traditional phylogenetic marker for prokaryotes, does not correlate well with the GC-content of the genome.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] For example, members of the Holosporales have a much higher ribosomal GC-content than members of the Pelagibacterales and Rickettsiales, though they are more closely related to species with high genomic GC-contents than to members of the latter two orders.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] Alphaproteobacteria are divided into three subclasses, Magnetococcidae, Rickettsidae, and Caulobacteridae.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] The basal group is Magnetococcidae, composed of a large diversity of magnetotactic bacteria only one of which, Magnetococcus marinus, is formally described.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] The Rickettsidae is composed of the intracellular Rickettsiales and the free-living Pelagibacterales.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] The Caulobacteridae is composed of the Holosporales, Rhodospirillales, Sphingomonadales, Rhodobacterales, Caulobacterales, Kiloniellales, Kordiimonadales, Parvularculales, and Sneathiellales.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] Comparative analyses of the sequenced genomes have revealed many conserved insertion-deletions (indels) in widely distributed proteins and whole proteins (i.e. signature proteins) that are distinctive characteristics of either all Alphaproteobacteria, or their different main orders (viz.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] Rhizobiales, Rhodobacterales, Rhodospirillales, Rickettsiales, Sphingomonadales and Caulobacterales) and families (viz.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] Rickettsiaceae, Anaplasmataceae, Rhodospirillaceae, Acetobacteraceae, Bradyrhiozobiaceae, Brucellaceae and Bartonellaceae).
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] These molecular signatures provide a means to circumscribe the taxonomic groups and to identify and assign new species accurately.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] Phylogenetic analyses and conserved indels in large numbers of other proteins provide evidence that Alphaproteobacteria have branched off later than most other phyla and classes of Bacteria except Betaproteobacteria and Gammaproteobacteria.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] Other phylogenetic debates turn on the placement of Magnetococcidae and the protomitochondrion.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] There are some debates for the inclusion of Magnetococcidae in Alphaproteobacteria.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] For example, an independent proteobacterial class ("*Candidatus* Etaproteobacteria") for Magnetococcidae has been proposed.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] A recent phylogenomic study suggests the placement of the protomitochondrial clade between Magnetococcidae and all other alphaproteobacterial taxa, which suggests an early divergence of the protomitochondrial lineage from the rest of alphaproteobacteria, except for Magnetococcidae.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] This phylogeny also suggests that the protomitochondrial lineage does not necessarily have a close relationship to Rickettsidae.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN).
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] The phylogeny is based on whole-genome analysis.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] Subclass names are based on Ferla *et al*.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] Although only a few studies have been reported on natural genetic transformation in the Alphaproteobacteria, this process has been described in *Agrobacterium tumefaciens*, *Methylobacterium organophilum*, and *Bradyrhizobium japonicum*.
[src:asgard-archaea/alphaproteobacteria] Natural genetic transformation is a sexual process involving DNA transfer from one bacterial cell to another through the intervening medium, and the integration of the donor sequence into the recipient genome by homologous recombination.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] After including the kingdom category into ICNP, the only validly published name of this group is kingdom Promethearchaeati.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] All formerly proposed "phyla" would be de-ranked to classes in this framework.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] In the summer of 2010, sediments were analysed from a gravity core taken in the rift valley on the Knipovich ridge in the Arctic Ocean, near the Loki's Castle hydrothermal vent site.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] Specific sediment horizons previously shown to contain high abundances of novel archaeal lineages were subjected to metagenomic analysis.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] In 2015, an Uppsala University-led team proposed the "Lokiarchaeota" phylum based on phylogenetic analyses using a set of highly conserved protein-coding genes.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] The group was named for the shape-shifting Norse god Loki, in an allusion to the hydrothermal vent complex from which the first genome sample originated.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] The Loki of mythology has been described as "a staggeringly complex, confusing, and ambivalent figure who has been the catalyst of countless unresolved scholarly controversies", analogous to the role of "Lokiarchaeota" in the debates about the origin of eukaryotes.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] In 2016, a University of Texas-led team discovered "Thorarchaeia" from samples taken from the White Oak River in North Carolina, named in reference to Thor, another Norse god.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] Researchers therefore named the group containing these microbes "Asgard", after the home of the gods in Norse mythology.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] Two "Lokiarchaeota" specimens have been cultured, enabling a detailed insight into their morphology.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] Superphylum "Asgard" was renamed to kingdom Promethearchaeati and phylum "Lokiarchaeota" was renamed to class Promethearchaeia.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] Asgard archaea encode many eukaryotic signature proteins, including novel GTPases, membrane-remodelling proteins like ESCRT and SNF7, a ubiquitin modifier system, and N-glycosylation pathway homologs.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] Asgard archaea have a regulated actin cytoskeleton, and the profilins and gelsolins they use can interact with eukaryotic actins.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] In addition, Asgard archaea tubulin from hydrothermal-living "Odinarchaeia" (OdinTubulin) was identified as a genuine tubulin.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] OdinTubulin forms protomers and protofilaments most similar to eukaryotic microtubules, yet assembles into ring systems more similar to FtsZ, indicating that OdinTubulin may represent an evolution intermediate between FtsZ and microtubule-forming tubulins.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] They also seem to form vesicles under cryogenic electron microscopy.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] They also share the three-way ES39 expansion in LSU rRNA with eukaryotes.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] Gene clusters or operons encoding ribosomal proteins are often less conserved in their organization in the Asgard archaea than in other archaea, suggesting that the order of ribosomal protein coding genes may follow the phylogeny.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] Asgard archaea are generally obligate anaerobes, though "Kariarchaeaceae", "Gerdarchaeales" and "Hodarchaeales" may be facultative aerobes.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] They have a Wood–Ljungdahl pathway and perform glycolysis.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] Members can be autotrophs, heterotrophs, or phototrophs using heliorhodopsin.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] One member, *Promethearchaeum syntrophicum*, is syntrophic with a sulfur-reducing proteobacteria and a methanogenic archaea.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] The RuBisCO they have is not carbon-fixing, but likely used for nucleoside salvaging.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] Asgard archaea are widely distributed around the world, both geographically and by habitat.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] Many of the known clades are restricted to sediments, whereas Promethearchaeia, "Thorarchaeia" and another clade occupy many different habitats.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] Salinity and depth are important ecological drivers for most Asgard archaea.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] Other habitats include the bodies of animals, the rhizosphere of plants, non-saline sediments and soils, the sea surface, and freshwater.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] In addition, Asgard archaea are associated with several other microorganisms.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] The class "Heimdallarchaeia" was found in 2017 to have N-terminal core histone tails, a feature previously thought to be exclusively eukaryotic.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] Two other archaeal phyla, both non-Asgard archaea, were found to also have tails in 2018.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] In January 2020, scientists found *Promethearchaeum syntrophicum*, a member of the Promethearchaeia, engaging in cross-feeding with two bacterial species.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] Drawing an analogy to symbiogenesis, they consider this relationship a possible link between the simple prokaryotic microorganisms and the complex eukaryotic microorganisms occurring approximately two billion years ago.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] The phylogenetic relationships of the Asgard archaea have been studied by several teams in the 21st century.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] Varying results have been obtained, for instance using 53 marker proteins from the Genome Taxonomy Database.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] In 2023, Eme, Tamarit, Caceres and colleagues reported that the Eukaryota are deep within Asgard archaea, as sister of "Hodarchaeales" within the "Heimdallarchaeia".
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] In the depicted scenario, the Eukaryota are deep in the Asgard archaeal tree.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] A favored scenario is syntrophy, where one organism depends on the feeding of the other.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] An α-proteobacterium was incorporated to become the mitochondrion.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] In culture, extant Asgard archaea form various syntrophic dependencies.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] Gregory Fournier and Anthony Poole have proposed that Asgard archaea is part of "the Eukaryote tree", forming a taxon they call "Eukaryomorpha" defined by "shared derived characters" (eukaryote signature proteins).
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] The kingdom contains one phylum, Promethearchaeota.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] Several family-level groups of viruses associated with Asgard archaea have been discovered using metagenomics.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] The viruses were assigned to Promethearchaeia, "Thorarchaeia", "Odinarchaeia" and "Helarchaeia" hosts using CRISPR spacer matching to the corresponding protospacers within the viral genomes.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] The viruses have been identified in deep-sea sediments and a terrestrial hot spring of the Yellowstone National Park.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] All these viruses display very low sequence similarity to other known viruses but are generally related to the previously described prokaryotic viruses, with no meaningful affinity to viruses of eukaryotes.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] In addition to viruses, several groups of cryptic mobile genetic elements have been discovered through CRISPR spacer matching to be associated with Asgard archaea of the Promethearchaeia, "Thorarchaeia" and "Heimdallarchaeia" lineages.
[src:asgard-archaea/asgard-archaea] These mobile elements do not encode recognizable viral hallmark proteins and could represent either novel types of viruses or plasmids.
